# Blood gas tension

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Jump to: navigation, search

**Blood gas tension** refers to the [partial pressure](/wiki/Partial_pressure
"Partial pressure") of [gases](/wiki/Gas "Gas") in [blood](/wiki/Blood
"Blood").[1] There are several significant purposes for measuring gas
tension;[2] the most common gas tensions measured are [oxygen](/wiki/Oxygen
"Oxygen") tension[3] (PxO2), the [carbon dioxide](/wiki/Carbon_dioxide "Carbon
dioxide") tension[3] (PxCO2) and [carbon monoxide](/wiki/Carbon_monoxide
"Carbon monoxide") tension[3] (PxCO). The subscript _x_ in each symbol
represents the source of the gas being measured; "_a_ " meaning
[arterial](/wiki/Artery "Artery"),[3] "_A_ " being
[alveolar](/wiki/Pulmonary_alveolus "Pulmonary alveolus"),[3] "_v_ " being
[venous](/wiki/Vein "Vein"),[3] "_c_ " being [capillary](/wiki/Capillary
"Capillary").[3] [Blood gas tests](/wiki/Blood_gas_test "Blood gas test")
(such as [arterial blood gas](/wiki/Arterial_blood_gas "Arterial blood gas")
tests) measure these partial pressures.

## Oxygen
tension[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Oxygen tension")]

Arterial blood oxygen tension (normal)

**P aO2** – Partial pressure of oxygen at sea level (765 [mmHg](/wiki/MmHg
"MmHg")) in [arterial blood](/wiki/Arterial_blood "Arterial blood") is between
75 mmHg and 100 mmHg.[4][5][6]

Venous blood oxygen tension (normal)

**P vO2** – Oxygen tension in [venous blood](/wiki/Venous_blood "Venous
blood") at sea level is between 30 mmHg and 40 mmHg.[6][7]

## Carbon dioxide
tension[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Carbon dioxide tension")]

Carbon dioxide is a by-product of food metabolism and in high amounts has
toxic effects including: [dyspnea](/wiki/Dyspnea "Dyspnea"),
[acidosis](/wiki/Acidosis "Acidosis") and [altered
consciousness](/wiki/Altered_consciousness "Altered consciousness").[8]

Arterial blood carbon dioxide tension

**[P aCO2](/wiki/PCO2 "PCO2")** – Partial pressure of carbon dioxide at sea
level (765 mmHg) in arterial blood is between 35 mmHg and 45 mmHg.[9]

Venous blood carbon dioxide tension

**P vCO2** – Partial pressure of carbon dioxide at sea level in venous blood
is between 40 mmHg and 50 mmHg.[9]

## Carbon monoxide
tension[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Carbon monoxide tension")]

Arterial carbon monoxide tension (normal)

**P aCO** – Partial pressure of CO at sea level (765 mmHg) in arterial blood
is approximately 0.02. It can be slightly higher in smokers and people living
in dense urban areas.

##
Significance[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=4
"Edit section: Significance")]

The partial pressure of gas in blood is significant because it is directly
related to ventilation and oxygenation.[10] When used alongside the pH balance
of the blood, the PaCO2 and HCO3 (and Lactate) suggest to the health care
practitioner which interventions, if any, should be made.[10][11]

## Equations[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=5
"Edit section: Equations")]

### Oxygen
content[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=6
"Edit section: Oxygen content")]

     C a O 2 = 1.36 ∗ H g b ∗ S a O 2 100 + 0.0031 ∗ P a O 2 {\displaystyle C_{a}O_{2}=1.36*Hgb*{\frac {S_{a}O_{2}}{100}}+0.0031*P_{a}O_{2}} ![C_{a}O_{2}=1.36*Hgb*{\\frac  {S_{a}O_{2}}{100}}+0.0031*P_{a}O_{2}](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/c3984de5fc0bff1b5af4cda5362132a73b15ba95)

The constant, 1.36, is the amount of oxygen (ml at 1 atmosphere) bound per
gram of [hemoglobin](/wiki/Hemoglobin "Hemoglobin"). The exact value of this
constant varies from 1.34 to 1.39, depending on the reference and the way it
is derived. The constant 0.0031 represents the amount of oxygen dissolved in
plasma. The dissolved-oxygen term is generally small relative to the term for
hemoglobin-bound oxygen, but becomes significant at very high PaO2 (as in a
[hyperbaric chamber](/wiki/Hyperbaric_chamber "Hyperbaric chamber")) or in
severe [anemia](/wiki/Anemia "Anemia").[12]

### Oxygen
saturation[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Blood_gas_tension&action=edit&section=7
"Edit section: Oxygen saturation")]

     S O 2 = ( 23 , 400 p O 2 3 + 150 p O 2 + 1 ) − 1 {\displaystyle SO_{2}=({\frac {23,400}{pO_{2}^{3}+150pO_{2}}}+1)^{-1}} ![SO_{2}=\({\\frac  {23,400}{pO_{2}^{3}+150pO_{2}}}+1\)^{{-1}}](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/dbe580da6b57a6f56538b235f32eff2a9ee14cd8)

This is an estimation and does not account for differences in temperature, pH
and concentrations of 2,3 DPG.[13]
